1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
What about this one? It's kind of badass, right?

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:08,000
Just seems kind of crazy in a way I might need right now.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:13,000
I don't know. Oh, that's not yours.

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:19,000
Stanley just drank OJ out of my mug and didn't seem to realize that it wasn't his hot coffee.

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:25,000
So the question has to be asked, is there no limit to what he won't notice?

6
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:31,000
Going to the kitchen, Stanley? Need anything?

7
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:33,000
I'll take a Milano.

8
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:37,000
Okay. Oh, you should just sign this for me before you go.

9
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Thank you.

10
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Maybe Stanley's just super focused. Maybe Stanley's completely checked out of life.

11
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:51,000
Maybe we weren't meant to know the answers. And who am I to play God?

12
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:54,000
I'm just a guy with time on his hands.

13
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:57,000
What's a seven-letter word for purse?

14
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:59,000
Satchel.

15
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:01,000
No, starts with an H.

16
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:03,000
Handbag.

17
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:06,000
Hmm, thank you.

18
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Shh, shh.

19
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:12,000
All right, everybody, take a seat.

20
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:18,000
As you may have heard, our branch on the planet Jupiter is up 8,000% in sales.

21
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:23,000
Yay!

22
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Hold up. That clock is slow. It is five o'clock. I will see you all tomorrow.

23
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,000
Bye, Stanley. Love you.

24
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:33,000
Bye.

25
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:35,000
It's long, Stanley.

26
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
Night, everybody.

27
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:07,000
So what kind of statement are you making with that costume, Kevin?

28
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:13,000
The statement that I am making, Oscar, is I kind of look like Michael Moore.

29
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Thunder Mifflin, this is Erin. Happy Halloween. How can I haunt you today?

30
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:21,000
A lot of people are really getting into Halloween this year.

31
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:25,000
Six seconds, McRubble. Pan's got a lot of fun stuff planned.

32
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:27,000
Two seconds, McRubble.

33
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Including a costume contest and bombing for apples and a Ouija board.

34
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:36,000
Oh, boom! Oh, explosion! McRubble!

35
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:39,000
People are really into the costume contest this year.

36
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Might have something to do with the prize. Maybe you've heard of it.

37
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:49,000
The 2011 Scranton Wilkes-Barre coupon book worth over $15,000 in savings.

38
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:55,000
The 2011 Scranton Wilkes-Barre coupon book worth over $15,000 in savings.

39
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:02,000
Stop. Too late. If I was the real Scranton Strangler, you'd be so strangled by now.

40
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:07,000
If you're out there, Strangler, you will get caught. By me.

41
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:10,000
Sounds like someone's really trying to convince us that he's not the Scranton Strangler.

42
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
To my chickens, I'm the Scranton Strangler.

43
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:16,000
Oh, ho. That's very funny.

44
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:19,000
Looks like someone decided to dress up as old Dwight Schrute's mom.

45
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:20,000
What?

46
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,000
You're only one third as beautiful and about half her height.

47
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:26,000
I'm supposed to be olive oil. And it makes more sense when I'm standing next to Popeye.

48
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,000
But Jim doesn't want to put his costume on.

49
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:33,000
I am Popeye. I've never really been a costume guy.

50
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,000
Even when I was a kid, it just felt like something I was too old for.

51
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:41,000
And then this morning, Pam hands me this little number.

52
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,000
No.

53
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:51,000
In case you can't read my poker face, we will be reviewing our sales policies.

54
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:55,000
I have ten seconds to explain them or this whole place blows up.

55
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,000
MacGruber!

56
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:01,000
Lame. Why don't witches wear panties?

57
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,000
Oh, here we go.

58
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,000
Because they need to grip the brook.
